00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:04.800
So just to kind of echo what was already shared was really great.

00:51:04.800 --> 00:51:10.679
And sometimes, you know, the, the modeling and everything that we do goes well, and we

00:51:10.679 --> 00:51:15.239
find out the answers that we want to know, but for the business, they might've gotten

00:51:15.239 --> 00:51:21.760
in there with some very specific expectations, like just generically launching a new product

00:51:21.760 --> 00:51:26.520
is going to lead to this big halo effect on a parent brand, for example, and we might

00:51:26.520 --> 00:51:29.120
not find that that's the case.

00:51:29.120 --> 00:51:36.320
But in order to make it so that the work we did is valuable, sometimes it takes even more

00:51:36.320 --> 00:51:39.199
than one discussion or presentation.

00:51:39.199 --> 00:51:45.199
And what, you know, what can you add to your results for context that allows them to do

00:51:45.199 --> 00:51:46.199
something with that?

00:51:46.199 --> 00:51:51.879
And it might be like, well, we didn't see a halo effect, but we also did not see cannibalization,

00:51:51.879 --> 00:51:52.879
which is a good thing.

00:51:52.879 --> 00:51:59.719
And you can bring in, you know, other strategic studies and other information that's valuable

00:51:59.719 --> 00:52:04.159
that maybe isn't work that you did, but that's already been done in that area just for additional

00:52:04.159 --> 00:52:05.159
context.

00:52:05.199 --> 00:52:09.719
Yeah, I find sometimes spending just as much time, if not more, on how do we present our

00:52:09.719 --> 00:52:14.879
results, how do we explain things to people so it makes sense and they can do something

00:52:14.879 --> 00:52:20.760
with it than just doing the analysis and here's the results for our modeling.

00:52:20.760 --> 00:52:25.080
Like sometimes it takes a lot of work and how do you communicate that out?

00:52:25.080 --> 00:52:27.600
And these days, that's what I spend most of my time doing.

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:32.159
I don't get to do as much fun coding and stuff anymore, but I do a lot of presentations and

00:52:32.159 --> 00:52:34.399
discussions and stuff like that.

00:52:34.639 --> 00:52:38.239
So I think that part of the work is also just as important.

00:52:38.239 --> 00:52:40.239
So hopefully that's helpful.

00:52:40.239 --> 00:52:42.320
Yeah, definitely.

00:52:42.320 --> 00:52:45.320
I think what you do probably adds more value.

00:52:45.320 --> 00:52:53.840
I find it a lot harder to do sometimes, but it's important.

00:52:53.840 --> 00:52:59.439
How do you explain that in a way that makes sense and what can we learn from that?

00:52:59.760 --> 00:53:05.320
We even had a lot of times a lower adoption rate for the work that we were doing and they

00:53:05.320 --> 00:53:12.280
would just go to external companies because they might be more likely to maybe think they're

00:53:12.280 --> 00:53:14.199
getting better results or something like that.

00:53:14.199 --> 00:53:19.520
But sometimes you just learn like, well, if we had this other kind of data, maybe we could

00:53:19.520 --> 00:53:21.320
do a better job with this.

00:53:21.320 --> 00:53:25.639
So even just pointing out things that might be missing that would be helpful and that

00:53:25.639 --> 00:53:30.639
at least gives them something to go off of, not just like we didn't see the sales that we

00:53:30.639 --> 00:53:32.959
wanted. We could add in there.

00:53:33.520 --> 00:53:35.800
I think Veronica mentioned alternatives.

00:53:35.800 --> 00:53:38.360
So in that line as well, I think that's great as well.

00:53:38.360 --> 00:53:41.479
Sometimes it just takes thinking outside the box a little bit.

00:53:41.479 --> 00:53:46.479
But it's super helpful just to think about all the ways that you can explain why it's still

00:53:46.479 --> 00:53:49.040
helpful, even if you don't see what you wanted to see.

00:53:52.719 --> 00:53:54.600
Thank you, Alan.

00:53:54.760 --> 00:53:56.399
You had some thoughts on this, too.

00:53:56.399 --> 00:53:57.800
Do you want to go next?

00:53:58.719 --> 00:54:03.439
Oh, yeah, sure. I think I was just emphasizing that how important it is, I think, for

00:54:03.879 --> 00:54:09.360
experimentation and exploratory analysis and so on to be really rooted in the domain that

00:54:09.360 --> 00:54:13.800
you're in, the business domain that you're working in so that you have some kind of clear

00:54:13.800 --> 00:54:18.879
expectation for what you're going to find and what you'll do, what kinds of decisions will be

00:54:18.879 --> 00:54:21.760
made one way versus another way based on what you find.

00:54:22.520 --> 00:54:28.080
The tension that I've experienced are when folks are kind of distant from a business

00:54:28.080 --> 00:54:33.280
perspective. I think this is why analysts and data scientists need to be really rooted and

00:54:33.280 --> 00:54:35.439
embedded in the business that they work with.

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:42.719
Often folks who are who are not have this idea that, well, we'll just explore and an insight

00:54:42.719 --> 00:54:48.239
will be emergent. And you can find interesting things that way, but you can't get

00:54:48.239 --> 00:54:52.560
direction on what you do, what's valuable to your stakeholders, to your customers.

00:54:53.600 --> 00:54:58.399
And so I think that even when you're experimenting and exploring, I think being rooted in

00:54:58.719 --> 00:55:03.439
like what's the work about, what do we want to find, what do we want to answer and what will we

00:55:03.439 --> 00:55:08.199
do differently based on it is just is just super important.

00:55:09.320 --> 00:55:13.959
And when folks ask for like, well, I need reports to do all of the following things, then you

00:55:13.959 --> 00:55:15.959
can really say, like, well, what are you going to do?

00:55:16.280 --> 00:55:20.320
Then we can be really focused and we can find what you're looking for, successful or not.

00:55:20.320 --> 00:55:21.800
We at least know if we found it.

00:55:22.120 --> 00:55:24.080
So I just think that's super, super important.

00:55:25.560 --> 00:55:28.399
Totally. Mike, I see your hands up.

00:55:28.959 --> 00:55:34.679
Back to me again. One example of a thing that really irritates me as the lead of a group

00:55:34.679 --> 00:55:42.000
or an SME is when someone will take an example like, hey, I'd like to I'd like to use

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:47.360
Python to recreate all the dplyr functions because I'd like to learn dplyr, I'd like to learn

00:55:47.360 --> 00:55:56.280
Python. And it's like, OK, that's valid to a point, but you could do all today in R using

00:55:56.280 --> 00:55:59.399
dplyr. So what are we doing here?

00:55:59.600 --> 00:56:01.159
What are you actually doing?

00:56:01.320 --> 00:56:03.840
Are you learning Python just for the sake of it?

00:56:04.320 --> 00:56:09.080
Or and once you're done, what is going to happen with the experiment that you've just done

00:56:09.080 --> 00:56:16.760
here? Is this just for you to learn something which is valid, but if you're doing

00:56:16.760 --> 00:56:21.800
something for the business to move the business forward, that experiment may not be the

00:56:21.800 --> 00:56:23.239
best use of your time.

00:56:24.159 --> 00:56:29.560
I love this unexpected direction we went here with experimentation.

00:56:31.120 --> 00:56:36.840
I know we have just a few minutes left here, so rather than jumping into a new discussion, I

00:56:36.840 --> 00:56:42.040
just want to say thank you so much to everybody here for just kind of jumping in on our chaos

00:56:42.040 --> 00:56:49.439
mode here. I would love to have Joel join us back again when we figure out our Wi-Fi

00:56:49.439 --> 00:56:54.040
issues so we can give him the session we wanted to have with him and get to learn from his

00:56:54.040 --> 00:56:59.280
experience. But thank you all for for jumping in here and still making this a great

00:56:59.280 --> 00:57:03.399
hangout. Always happy to be here.

00:57:04.399 --> 00:57:05.399
Thank you all so much.

00:57:05.679 --> 00:57:06.560
Have a great rest of the day.

00:57:06.840 --> 00:57:07.639
Bye, everybody.

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:08.399
Bye, everyone.

